1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,140
In this lesson, we're going to look at plot matrices.

2
00:00:03,140 --> 00:00:06,335
Let's start by doing our normal imports.

3
00:00:06,335 --> 00:00:08,845
What is a plot matrix?

4
00:00:08,845 --> 00:00:11,490
Well, let's say we're interested in looking at

5
00:00:11,490 --> 00:00:15,750
the pairwise relationships between all of our numeric variables.

6
00:00:15,750 --> 00:00:18,600
Instead of plotting scatter plots one by one,

7
00:00:18,600 --> 00:00:21,840
we might want to just inspect them all at once.

8
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:25,500
That is the subject of this lesson.

9
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:29,565
That's using what's called plot matrices.

10
00:00:29,565 --> 00:00:35,090
Let's start by importing our normal functions for data analysis and visualization,

11
00:00:35,090 --> 00:00:38,875
as well as loading our fuel economy dataset.

12
00:00:38,875 --> 00:00:41,315
To create a plot matrix,

13
00:00:41,315 --> 00:00:44,405
we can just use seaborns pair grid function.

14
00:00:44,405 --> 00:00:51,305
Note that I'm only focusing on four specific variables here: highway efficiency,

15
00:00:51,305 --> 00:00:56,320
city efficiency, engine size, and CO_2 emissions.

16
00:00:56,320 --> 00:01:01,325
If we do not specify the variables parameter,

17
00:01:01,325 --> 00:01:03,785
the V-A-R-S or vars parameter.

18
00:01:03,785 --> 00:01:08,615
We will plot then a matrix of all numeric variables.

19
00:01:08,615 --> 00:01:14,645
It's going to take a very long time to generate and it'll just be a lot to read.

20
00:01:14,645 --> 00:01:18,385
Instead, I just want to focus on these here.

21
00:01:18,385 --> 00:01:26,270
Also please note that I specify both the off-diagonal and diagonal elements.

22
00:01:26,270 --> 00:01:28,505
For the off-diagonal elements,

23
00:01:28,505 --> 00:01:31,795
I'm requesting seaborn to use scatter plots.

24
00:01:31,795 --> 00:01:35,835
For the diagonal elements I'm going to use histograms.

25
00:01:35,835 --> 00:01:40,490
For instance, if we look all of the rows and all of

26
00:01:40,490 --> 00:01:45,385
the columns are in the same order as the order that we gave.

27
00:01:45,385 --> 00:01:47,810
If we look along the diagonal,

28
00:01:47,810 --> 00:01:52,100
we will see in this first row and column, highway efficiency.

29
00:01:52,100 --> 00:01:54,710
This is a histogram of highway efficiency.

30
00:01:54,710 --> 00:01:59,995
Then the next diagonal element is city efficiency and so on.

31
00:01:59,995 --> 00:02:03,065
Looking at the first row and second column,

32
00:02:03,065 --> 00:02:07,220
we see that highway is our y axis,

33
00:02:07,220 --> 00:02:10,085
while city is our x-axis,

34
00:02:10,085 --> 00:02:12,590
and if we scroll down here,

35
00:02:12,590 --> 00:02:16,525
we see that the x label is correct.

36
00:02:16,525 --> 00:02:20,465
Likewise, for the third column and first row,

37
00:02:20,465 --> 00:02:23,495
we have highway versus engine displacement,

38
00:02:23,495 --> 00:02:27,155
so we see the bivariate plot there.

39
00:02:27,155 --> 00:02:31,130
Each row and each column works with a variable.

40
00:02:31,130 --> 00:02:33,620
For the diagonals as I said,

41
00:02:33,620 --> 00:02:36,060
we're only plotting one variable.

42
00:02:36,060 --> 00:02:39,275
I chose to display a histogram but

43
00:02:39,275 --> 00:02:43,975
a KDE or any other univariate plot would probably work well.

44
00:02:43,975 --> 00:02:47,030
Note also that there's a symmetry in a pair grid

45
00:02:47,030 --> 00:02:50,600
with x and y axes are flipped across the diagonal.

46
00:02:50,600 --> 00:02:54,875
In this way, by looking at the first row and second column,

47
00:02:54,875 --> 00:02:58,480
we see highway versus city efficiency.

48
00:02:58,480 --> 00:03:02,585
But if we then go to the opposite cell or the symmetric cell,

49
00:03:02,585 --> 00:03:06,715
we get city versus highway efficiency.

50
00:03:06,715 --> 00:03:09,315
The bivariate plot is flipped.

51
00:03:09,315 --> 00:03:12,830
For the diagonals, we only plot one variable.

52
00:03:12,830 --> 00:03:15,830
In this case, I chose to display a histogram but

53
00:03:15,830 --> 00:03:20,065
a KDE or other univariate plot would probably work well.

54
00:03:20,065 --> 00:03:24,500
Another useful thing common in analysis is plotting a correlation matrix.

55
00:03:24,500 --> 00:03:27,620
We do this by first extracting the correlation from

56
00:03:27,620 --> 00:03:31,270
the data frame and then dropping this into a heatmap.

57
00:03:31,270 --> 00:03:38,160
Here, we use the seaborn heatmap method and we just toss in the correlation.

58
00:03:38,160 --> 00:03:44,275
In this case, I'm only selecting the columns that we used earlier.

59
00:03:44,275 --> 00:03:47,120
Right here, this shows that city and

60
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:51,065
highway efficiency are highly correlated, which is not shocking.

61
00:03:51,065 --> 00:03:56,675
It also shows that engine size and emissions are highly correlated,

62
00:03:56,675 --> 00:03:59,035
which is also expected.

63
00:03:59,035 --> 00:04:01,550
Fuel efficiency and engine size,

64
00:04:01,550 --> 00:04:05,660
and therefore CO_2 emissions are highly anti-correlated.

65
00:04:05,660 --> 00:04:12,290
One thing to note is I added a vmin which is a vertical minimum of negative 1.

66
00:04:12,290 --> 00:04:16,700
This sets the minimum value of the color bar and seaborn.

67
00:04:16,700 --> 00:04:19,400
Also for correlation matrix,

68
00:04:19,400 --> 00:04:23,150
typically you want to make sure that they're square because they are

69
00:04:23,150 --> 00:04:29,040
symmetric and so you can pass in the parameter square equals true.

